The following index definition indexes the `title` field in the
[sample collection](custom-analyzers-eg-coll) collection using a custom
analyzer named `stopwordRemover`. The custom analyzer specifies the
following:* Apply the [whitespace](whitespace-tokenizer-ref)
  to create tokens based on occurrences of whitespace between words.

* Apply the `stopword` token filter to remove the tokens that
  match the defined stop words `is`, `the`, and `at`. The
  token filter is case-insensitive and will remove all tokens that
  match the specified stopwords.**Atlas UI:**Atlas UI<Tab tabid="vib">
  Visual Editor

  - In the Custom Analyzers section, click Add
    Custom Analyzer.

  - Select the Create Your Own radio button and click
    Next.

  - Type whitespace in the Analyzer Name field.

  - Expand Tokenizer if it's collapsed.

  - Select whitespace from the dropdown.

  - Expand Token Filters and click&#x20;
    Add token filter.

  - Select wordDelimiterGraph from the dropdown and type the
    following in the tokens field:

    `is`, `the`, `at`

  - Click Add token filter to add the token filter to your
    custom analyzer.

  - Click Add to create the custom analyzer.

  - In the Field Mappings section, click Add
    Field Mapping to apply the custom analyzer on
    the message field.

  - Select message from the Field
    Name dropdown and dateFacet from the Data
    Type dropdown.

  - In the properties section for the data type, select whitespace
    from the Index Analyzer and Search Analyzer
    dropdowns.

  - Click Add, then Save Changes.
</Tab>JSON EditorReplace the default index definition with the following example:```json
{
  "mappings": {
    "fields": {
      "text": {
        "type" : "document",
        "fields": {
          "en_US": {
            "type": "string",
            "analyzer": "stopwordRemover"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "analyzers": [
    {
      "name": "stopwordRemover",
      "charFilters": [],
      "tokenizer": {
        "type": "whitespace"
      },
      "tokenFilters": [
        {
          "type": "stopword",
          "tokens": ["is", "the", "at"]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```**Shell:**MongoDB Shell```javascript
db.minutes.createSearchIndex(
  "default",
  {
    "mappings": {
      "fields": {
        "text": {
          "type": "document",
          "fields": {
            "en_US": {
              "type": "string",
              "analyzer": "stopwordRemover"
            }
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "analyzers": [
      {
        "name": "stopwordRemover",
        "charFilters": [],
        "tokenizer": {
          "type": "whitespace"
        },
        "tokenFilters": [
          {
            "type": "stopword",
            "tokens": ["is", "the", "at"]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
)

```The following query searches for the phrase `head of the sales`
in the `text.en_US` field in the [sample collection](custom-analyzers-eg-coll) collection.**Atlas UI:**Atlas UI- Click the Query button for your index.

- Click Edit Query to edit the query.

- Click on the query bar and select the database and collection.

- Replace the default query with the following and click
  Search:

  **Input:**

  ```json
  {
    "$search": {
      "phrase": {
        "query": "head of the sales",
        "path": "text.en_US"
      }
    }
  }
  ```

  **Output:**

  ```json
  SCORE: 1.5351942777633667 _id:  "2"
    message: "do not forget to SIGN-IN. See ① for details."
    page_updated_by: Object
    text: Object
  ```**Shell:**MongoDB Shell**Input:**```json
db.minutes.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "phrase": {
        "query": "head of the sales",
        "path": "text.en_US"
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "text.en_US": 1
    }
  }
])
```**Output:**```js
[
  {
    _id: 2,
    text: { en_US: 'The head of the sales department spoke first.' }
  }
]
```MongoDB Search returns the document with `_id: 2` because the `en_US` field
contains the query term. MongoDB Search doesn't create tokens for the stopword
`the` in the document during analysis, but is still able to match
it to the query term because for `string` fields, it also analyzes
the query term using the index analyzer (or if specified, using the
`searchAnalyzer`) and removes the stopword from the query term,
which allows MongoDB Search to match the query term to the document.
Specifically, MongoDB Search creates the following tokens for the document in
the results:| Document ID | Output Tokens                              |
| ----------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| \_id: 2     | head, of, sales, department, spoke, first. |

